status: Japanese professional of the Inoue school.
name: Aihara Kaseki
note: Though little is known of him personally, he was a leading player in the important events of the early 18th century when the go world was rocked by a challenge from the shogi players over precedence. The Honinbos had lost their star players to early deaths, and Shuhaku, next in line, was very young and barely 7d, yet (as Honinbo, in the absence of a Meijin) was ranked first in the Godokoro. He too died early, during a challenge match to create some face for himself. His death allowed the shogi players to press their claim for alternation of the Godokoro and Shogidokoro as head of the games world, with other heads in either game ranked according to seniority, rather than ranked by seniority in go first, with shogi players (apart from the Shogidokoro, who ranked behind the Godokoro) bringing up the rear. The shogi claims were strengthened by having an outstanding Shogidokoro in Ito Sokan and a shogi-loving Commissioner of Shrines & Temples (the Jisha Bugyo) at the time, Lord Inoue of Kochi. However, he died (in Iyo) at a critical time, and the decision on precedence was passed to his successor, Lord Okada Tadasuke of Echizen, who was a go fan. This was where Aihara came in. He had been introduced to the Shogun Ienobu as a go prodigy at the age of 12 and had been given a considerable stipend of 60 bushels of rice a year, 10 bushels higher than the family heads. He also had a splendid mansion in Mita. Ienobu was a lover of both go and shogi, and other young players of both games had been introduced to him at the same time (Tsubota Ganseki, plus shogi players Miyamoto Insa and Ariura Inri). But Aihara had a chance to shine above the others when the Ryukyuan mission visited Japan in 1711 and he handsomely defeated Yara no Satonushi. He had to take White and it was seen as a major responsibility. His play at 13 was considered worthy of a family head. He was an obvious candidate to play in castle games, but this was considered inappropriate because of his close connection with the shogun. Instead he devoted his efforts to training the young Honinbo. This, and his international victory, cemented go's leading position and the shogi challenge died out. His last known game was in 1763. He reached 7d but was largely lost to the go world through being obliged to serve Ienobu personally.

status: Computer go program, in different versions, developed by Google DeepMind in London.
career: In 2015-10, it became the first program to beat a professional human Go player (Fan Hui 2d), 5-0 without handicaps, on a 19×19 board. On 2016-03-15 it similarly beat Yi Se-tol 4-1, the first time a program has beaten a 9-dan professional without handicaps. After defeating Yi Se-tol in an even-game. As a result it was awarded honorary 9d by the Korean Baduk Association.
name: AlphaGo
note: The DeepMind team was founded by Demis Hassabis who learnt go at Cambridge University. Hassabis sold DeepMind to Google in 2014 for reportedly £400 million. After the matches with Fan and Yi, the program also used the names Master (Masterの碁 or AlphaGo大师) and Magister in online games, and it also became common retrospectively to refer to the version that played Yi Se-tol as AlphaGo Lee. Then in October 2017 a superior version called AlphaGo Zero was announced. This was produced by training the program from scratch with zero input of human games. It reached its maximum strength after 70 days, and games were released showing progress after 3 days, 19 days and 70 days, and also games at full strength against the Master version, which did have some human database input. It also differs from previous versions in other notable ways. The final Zero (as of October 2017) version: only used the black and white stones from the go board as its input, whereas previous versions of AlphaGo included a small number of hand-engineered features; used one neural network rather than two (earlier versions used a policy network to select the next moves to play and a value network to predict the winner of the game from each position; these were combined in AlphaGo Zero); AlphaGo Zero does not use rollouts (fast, random games from current position) as used by other programs to predict winner, but relies on its high quality neural networks for evaluations.
matches: Beat Fan Hui 5-0 (2015). Beat Yi Se-tol 4-1 (2016). At end 2016 it played 60 games with top pros online under blitz conditions and won all 60.
gostyle: (Of its earliest forms, playing humans) Fan Hui: "Calm and conservative." An Yeong-kil: "Slightly territorial but well-balanced." Michael Redmond: "More aggressive and unorthodox." Mi Yuting: "It doesn't worry so much about the local position, and its global judgement is extremely strong."

status: Chinese professional with the Chinese Go Association (originally a middle-school teacher in Shanghai).
career: Learnt go at age 7. He won the Shanghai Championship in 1959 and was graded unofficially as +5d in 1964 (earned in 1962 but granted later). +9d 1981.
name: Chen Zude
note: He joined the Communist Party in 1977 but suffered during the Cultural Revolution and also rested from go 1980~90 to recover from cancer (contracted in 1980). In this period he received national honours such as the 1983 and 1986 Physical Education Badge of Honour and the Nationally Excelling Sportsman award. Regarded as a veteran pioneer of modern Chinese go - defined as the wave of players that strove to beat the Japanese 9-dans - he was first to beat one (Sugiuchi Masao, 1962-09-27, taking first-move handicap). He became first President of the Chinese Weiqi Association on 1991-10-24 and also held presidential posts for xiangqi (Chinese chess) and international chess. He was also deputy chairman of the China-Korea Goodwill Association. Regarded as the populariser of the Chinese fuseki (early 1960s). He has written or edited many books, including historical reprints. Some Chinese sources have birthdate 1944-02-19, which is the lunar date. It was announced that he would retire from his official posts in May 2003. A fracture of his foot revealed that he had osteoporosis and was therefore advised to take precautions.

career: 1d 1968, 2d 1968, 3d 1969, 4d 1970, 5d 1971, 6d 1973, 7d 1975, 8d 1978, 9d 1981. On April 27, 2017-04-27, after 49 years 0 months and at age 60 years 10 months, he became the first pro in Japan to reach 1,500 official wins, with a record of 1500-821-3-4. In that period he had beaten 307 opponents, and had never had a negative score in any year. But in 2018 he scored 14-16, the first time since qualifying as a pro 51 years ago that he has had a negative score. On 2023-12-25, he became the first pro in Japan to reach 1,600 official wins, with a record of 1600-89-3-4 at age 67.
name: Cho Chikun
note: He was born into an upper-class and wealthy family in Seoul (his paternal grandfather was a bank director and it was he who taught go to Chikun's father and Cho Nam-ch'eol, and his mother also came from a family of investors), but the family was impoverished by the Korean War when his father, Nam-seok, was obliged, a pistol at his head, to burn all his cash to avoid death, and was also unable to find work after the war. Chikun, the second youngest of seven children (two elder brothers, one younger who died in infancy, and three girls), moved to Japan in 1962-08 at the initiative of elder brother Cho Shoen who later effectively became his manager. The brothers all had the character yeon in their names (see Cho Shoen) and Chikun was originally called Pung-yeon. But an amateur fortune-teller told the family that if Pung-yeon did not change his name his mother would die, whereas if he did his baby brother would die but then Pung-yeon would become famous. So his father renamed him Chikun. The baby did die, despite constant attention. A professional fortune-teller later predicted that Chikun would become a famous person known to all in Korea. He has no recollection himself but it is said he learnt go from his grandfather - his father was too weak, never getting beyond 5-6 kyu. But when he showed aptitude for the game it was his father who decided he should go to Japan. He flew off with Cho Nam-ch'eol to join Kitani's school (his brother Cho Shoen had also already gone to Japan a year earlier) and the very next day he was pitted against Rin Kaiho, then 6d, at the Sankei Hall in front of a vast public. He took the game very seriously, folding his arms as he sank into thought, and had to be nudged to play faster for the audience, although he had actually been told to by his uncle and brother to fold his arms before every move to avoid the possibility of making errors through playing too fast. He won the game (1962-08-02). About a year after joining Kitani, he also enrolled as a 10-kyu insei at the Nihon Ki-in. He found it hard, being beaten down from 5 stones handicap to 9 stones in straight games (the handicap was adjusted after every game) against fellow Kitani disciple Kato Masao, for example, and on two occasions he even had to take ten stones. He was often reduced to tears but he made an impression by doggedly playing on with eyes streaming. Other children were apt to bully him - he was after all not Japanese. But as the baby of the Kitani family he was also rather indulged, and took advantage by being, by his own admission, a naughty child and he told fibs. His go studies suffered because he was cheeky to his fellow pupils and so they would not play teaching games, though they also recognised he was clever. His neglect of study was made more noticeable by the arrival of his future rival Kobayashi Koichi in the school. Kobayashi was three years older and weaker, but he studied very hard. Cho settled down somewhat at the age of seven when his mother, Ok-sun, came to Japan and comforted him by allowing him to suckle again. A crisis arose when his mother decided it was time to go home, but one famous incident that made Cho himself stick it out in Japan was when he was taken to the house of a wealthy patron of Kitani in Kobe, Takeoka Shiro (executive director of the Obayashi-gumi). Takeoka owned a large painting of a tiger. When Cho saw it he was goggle-eyed. Takeoka offered it to him, but Kitani interceded to impose a condition: he could have it if he reached 1d by the age of ten. In fact he did not reach this status until he was 11, but Mrs Kitani phoned Takeoka anyway and the present was duly delivered. It was probably Mrs Kitani who was most influential in keeping Cho in Japan - she adored him and spoilt him when he was very young - but the topic of a return to Korea was always in everyone's thoughts, including hers. He wore her out, he engaged in battles of will with her, and she more than once expressed misgivings to her husband about being able to give him a suitable upbringing. But one little incident that helped changed the mood was taking him to Mitsukoshi to buy his first suit - he was wreathed in smiles for a change. Mr Kitani volunteered to talk to Cho Nam-ch'eol about sending Chikun home, but he had another Korean pupil, Ha Ch'an-seok, who become a good friend of Chikun and the tribulations were tided over. It was Chikun himself who made the major change necessary when he did not make 1d at the age of 10, for it was his failure to do that that suddenly spurred him on to become a ferocious student. The tag of being a "difficult" child began to fade. He remains, however, a person of great passion. He claims he thinks of death whenever he loses, and he cannot stand being second. But in his career since then he has not often had to accept second best. He suffered a major traffic accident in 1986-01 but his legendary determination came to the fore and became the only player to contest a title match in a temporary wheelchair and plaster cast, in the Kisei. He holds, or held, several major records in tournament play: youngest 1d (11), youngest 9d in Nihon Ki-in (24, after 110 games with a winning percentage of 80.5%), youngest title holder (17 years 0 months: Shinei Tournament 1973 - since overtaken by Iyama Yuta), youngest major title winner (Pro Best 10, aged 18 in 1975), first to win Big Three titles (Kisei, Meijin, Honinbo, in 1983, repeated in 1996). He became the 25th Lifetime Honinbo after winning this tournament for a record 10 successive terms in 1998. 5th player to record 1,000 wins. He equalled Sakata Eio's record of 64 titles on 2002-08-17 when he won the 35th Hayago Championship (his tally began in 1973 with the 5th Shinei). He has since (as of 2006-07 with the 44th Judan) taken the total to 69, not counting pair go titles. He became the youngest to reach 1200 career wins on 2005-01-27 (third to this target after Kato Masao and Rin Kaiho), and became 2nd to record 1300 career wins on Japan in 2008-06-19 (681 losses, 3 jigo, 4 void). His Honinbo style is Honinbo Chikun. He is the nephew of Cho Nam-ch'eol, younger brother of Cho Shoen, cousin of Ch'oe Myeong-hun and uncle of Yi Seong-chae, and distantly related to Ch'oe Kyu-pyeong. His daughter became an insei in 1990, which became the occasion for Cho (very unusually for A leading player) to become for two years an insei instructor to "repay his debt" to Japanese go. Although he retains Korean nationality, he has a Japanese wife and Japanese is now his main language. As of 2010-12-02 he became the holder of the record for most career wins (1364-733-3-4), one ahead of Rin Kaiho. His Honinbo style is 本因坊治勲. He was awarded the Medal of Honour with Purple Ribbon in 2019. The birthdate 1956-07-23 is also given in the literature. He became the first player to hold the top three titles (Kisei, Honinbo, Meijin) simultaneously on two separate occasions, in 1996.

gostyle: "My game consists in bringing everything together without using set patterns of play. This absence of style is my style." He experiments in the opening: "My failing is that I tend to make extensions that are too wide." He dislikes large-scale josekis. In his early days he was noted for power and sharpness, plus tenacity, rather than suji or katachi. He is good at shinogi. When young he was full of youthful and inventive spirit, playing on a large scale, rather like Takemiya.

name: Cho Hun-hyeon
note: His family moved to Seoul, Korea when he was four and he learned go there by copying others. At age 6 he played Cho Nam-ch'eol on 9 stones and became an insei at age 7. He became 1d in Korea in 1962 (youngest ever, age 9) and 2d in 1963 but in October that year he moved to Japan to study as a live-in pupil under Segoe Kensaku, becoming an insei again but now 4k under the Japanese system. In Japan he reached both 1d and 2d in 1967. At this time he was also studying under Fujisawa Hideyuki, but returned to Korea as 5d in 1972-03 to complete his military service in the air force (where he suffered some discrimination because of his Japanese links). His score while a pro in Japan was 118-41-5 (1967: 14-8-1; 1968: 19-9-2; 1969:. 20-9-1; 1970: 33-5-1; 1971: 30-9; 1972: 2-1). His Japanese grade was accepted in Korea and reached 9d there (the first in Korea) in 1982. By far the most prolific winner of titles in Korean go, he held all nine titles in 1980. He was also the first player to win all (then) three international titles (Ing, Fujitsu and Tong Yang). He was the second Korean to record 1,000 wins (in 1995 after 34 years, but his games during his professional years in Japan are excluded). On 2004-06-22 he played his 2,000th game, the third player after Seo Pong-su and Rin Kaiho to do so. His career record at end 2004-06 was 1422-556-4. He is known for his habit of humming Japanese songs during matches. He reached 2,500 career games in 2008 (as of then his record was 1770-721 with 9 void).

gostyle: Orthodox. Master of technique and quick, fighting jabs leading to a roundhouse knockout blow - the Sugar Ray Leonard of go. He became more dour, however, as a way of combating Yi Ch'ang-ho. He claimed to be the best fuseki player in the world and has the ability to "shake" - to create chaos as a way of turning the tide of battle, though his battles are not showdowns but rather a way of maintaining or shifting positional superiority. He prefers to play the best rather than the safe move. Distinguished by nimble haengma and what have been called "aerobatic manoeuvres" - various nicknames relate to this: Swallow Cho, Flame-thrower Cho, Magician Cho.

name: Cho Nam-ch'eol
note: He returned to Korea in 1944. When Korea was liberated from Japan in 1945 he devoted himself to establishing professional go there (it had previously been regarded only as a gambling game). He founded first the Seoul Go Association (Hanseong Kiweon) in 1945, followed by the Korean Go Association (Choseon Kiweon) in 1948 and a larger Korean Go Association (Taehan Kiweon) in 1949. He was aided by two other players who, in 1950, became with him Korea's first three 1ds, but Cho was almost immediately promoted straight to 3d 1950. He won 30 titles and set a record as the oldest Korean to qualify for the final stages of a tournament (aged 71 in the 18th Kukgi in 1994 - he was actually 70 on day of the qualifying game, but was 71 by the time the main event started). He is regarded as the father of modern Korean go, recognised by his status as an honorary Taekuksu 大國手 (daguoshou or meijin). Among several major awards is award of the Okura Prize in Japan in 1984. He was the author of the first modern Korean go book that defined terminology (1955). His collected games were issued in 2002. He is the uncle of Cho Chikun and Cho Shoen. He was inducted into the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame in 2019.

status: Korean-born professional at the Nihon Ki-in.
career: He was originally a professional from age 15 in the Korean Go Association in Korea and became the No. 2 player there, behind his uncle Cho Nam-ch'eol, at age 18. He moved to Japan against the wishes of his parents and uncle in 1961 (he retained his membership of the Korean Go Association but was later expelled after siding with the losing side in a factional battle) to study at the Kansai Ki-in. When Kitani Minoru heard that a nephew of Cho Nam-ch'eol was in Japan he invited him to study with him (1961). He continued there but soon realised he was too old to compete with his fellow disciples for high honours and so devoted his efforts to bringing his younger brother Cho Chikun to Japan at the age of six - he had a major task to convince the boy's parents and Japan's visa authorities. +2d 1963, 3d 1972, 4d 1975, 5d 1983. Nephew of Cho Nam-ch'eol and elder brother of Cho Chikun. Owner of Korean go publishing house Ajim. He tried to gain reinstatement to the Korean Go Association in 2010 but did not get sufficient votes.

name: Felix Dueball
note: He first visited Japan in 1930-05, to study go for just over a year. He is regarded as the first westerner to be a foreign go student in Japan. He met all the top players, becoming good enough to take five stones. When he left he was given a 1d diploma (effectively honorary) and had a farewell reception hosted by the Mayor of Tokyo, Japan and attended by the likes of Baron Okura and Go Seigen. His second visit to Japan was to be a guest of honour at the first International Tournament in 1963. He played the future prime minister Hatoyama Ichiro in the first international telegraph game in 1936-10. Recipient in first Okura Prizes, 1964. The ue and not u umlaut is correct. His eldest son Fritz Dueball was the European champion in its first three terms (1957-1959). His other son Kurt and grandson Juergen were also go players. Nominated for the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame in 2021, the first westerner.

status: Engineer and chess player who took an avid interest in go and was an early author in the USA.
name: Edward Lasker
note: He learned go with Max Lange from a magazine in 1905 when studying engineering in Berlin. They soon stopped playing as they found the game shallow, but were later surprised to see a Japanese man, Kitabatake Yasugoro, in a café reading a paper with a go column in it. They retrieved the paper and played over the game after deciphering the numerals and decided Black was ahead. But only 150 moves were given (i.e. White had won) and they were curious as to why. They later found the same man and he told them Black had resigned. Astonished, they re-examined the game and decided go was not so shallow after all. They started playing regularly with the Japanese man, and soon reached his grade. After about 18 months Emanuel Lasker, world chess champion, having just returned from 14 years in America, joined them and picked up the game quickly - he arranged go evenings at his house. Emanuel Lasker eventually was giving Kitabatake two stones, and when news came that a Japanese 1d would be passing through Berlin and would play them on 9 stones, he said, "There isn't a man in the world who can give me 9 stones. I have studied the game for a year and I know I understood what they were doing." But, despite playing in consultation and playing slowly, he was crushed and was heartbroken. Edward Lasker, however, was inspired to go to Tokyo to study go. By then working for the Allgemeine Elektrizitäts Gesellschaft in Berlin, he asked for a transfer but was told he needed to speak English first. He therefore asked for a transfer to England in 1912-09. While there, war broke out. He was shipped to America rather than interned, thanks to a chess friend (he had won the London Championship in 1914). In New York he met go players Karl Davis Robinson and Harper's Magazine editor Lee Foster Hartman, but he went to live in Chicago until 1925. He then returned to New York and set up a go club with Robinson and Hartman and some German immigrants at Lee Chumley's, a Greenwich Village restaurant. In 1934 he wrote a popular go primer, _[_Go and Go Moku_]_. He also played with many mathematicians at Princeton University. Japanese Minister of Education Hatayama Ichiro played Lasker on a visit to New York in the thirties, and he was also visited at home by Tsushima Juichi and received a Nihon Ki-in diploma. His go strength would probably be about 1d amateur today. Edward and Emanuel Lasker were related as thirds cousins twice removed, and Edward did sometimes refer to Emanuale specifically as a cousin, though at other times he cited him as either a close relative or a distant relative.

status: Japanese professional at the Nihon Ki-in Main (Tokyo) Branch.
name: Fujisawa Hideyuki
note: Originally called Fujisawa Tamotsu 藤沢保, he changed his given name to Hideyuki in 1944, to acknowledge a patron, but the reading Shuko しゅうこう became widespread, against his wishes. Late in life he indicated he wished everyone to revert to Hideyuki but conceded that Shuko could be retained in usages such as Shuko's Study Tours. In his youth, after the second world war, he was classed as one of the Three Crows, along with Kajiwara Takeo and Yamabe Toshiro. At that time he was nicknamed Paranormal Fujisawa 異常感覚藤沢 (in the sense of having unusual sensitivity or aestheticism) by the writer pen-named Gengenshi. He was famous for living life to the full and as a man of extremes. As a fledgling professional in 1941 he lost all eight games in the Spring Oteai, then won all eight in the Autumn session. He won fame for winning (and then holding on to) the first Kisei title (one of several first titles he won) while making little impression elsewhere (though he did win 24 titles). He survived cancer three times and set a record for the oldest player (66) to defend a title (the Oza). He went against the grain of many Japanese in helping the Chinese, especially Nie Weiping, become strong, and he was also a notable moral supporter of Cho Hun-hyeon when the latter was struggling to win acceptance in Korea. His "Shuko" trips where he led young Japanese professionals overseas have also been influential. His collected games (1300+) were published in 1994. His tournament record was 863 wins, 655 losses and 8 ties. In 1999-11 he left the Nihon Ki-in to start his own business of issuing diplomas to amateurs - Nihon Ki-in diplomas were being criticised by him as too expensive, and he was critical also of some management. This led to a bitter war of words and the Ki-in formally expelled him in 1999-12. They afterwards refused to republish his books, but he returned in July 2003, by which time the Nihon Ki-in had new reform-minded directors and preparations for its 80th anniversary were looming. He was awarded the Medal of Honour with Purple Ribbon in 1987 and the Order of the Rising Sun, Gold Rays with Neck Ribbon (III) in 1997. The above birth-date is the one given in his autobiography "Gouchi Shuko" [_[_Gouchi Shuukou_]_] but Kido Yearbooks and other sources give the date 06-14, which was the date his birth was incorrectly registered at. It was not officially corrected until he got married. He died of aspiration pneumonia. He is the son of Fujisawa Jugoro, step-uncle of Fujisawa Hosai (even though older), father of Fujisawa Kazunari and grandfather of Fujisawa Rina. He was inducted into the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame in 2020.

status: Chinese daguoshou and the most famous player of his generation in the early 17th century.
name: Guo Bailing
note: He was the first author of the classic _[_Guanzi Pu_]_ (Manual of Endgame Problems), first published around 1660 and eventually published in its present form in 1689. Styled Guo Wennian 过文年. He was the scion of one of the illustrious families of the Wuxi region. The main source is his biography in _[_Cangxian-ji_]_ (Green Mountain Collection) by his fellow townsman Qin Songling. It says he was gifted and loved reading. He also liked playing go. A famous poem about him suggests he learnt go at the age of eight, but in any event Qin says that when in his 11th year, by watching others play, he understood about territory and void areas, sente and gote, the relationship between attack and defence and methods of managing them - and declared that go was not difficult. He played older players yet always won. His name reverberated around Wuxi. At that time an important official called Ye Xianggao (1558~1627, but as he graduated as jinshi in 1583 and became a Minister in 1607 this must have been between these dates, c. 1600), who was a Provincial Education Commissioner (xuetai) and later a Grand Secretary, came to Wuxi on business. He liked to play go and was at the level of taking two stones from a guoshou. He wanted to seek out the strongest player and play with him. Guo was therefore invited to attend. When Ye saw he was a mere boy he was quite astounded. Initially he did not believe Guo was his opponent, and then against his expectations he lost three games in a row. In the course of these games someone whispered to Guo that he was playing against a senior minister and should let him win one game. Although young Guo was already rather mature and angrily replied that, although go was a minor art, it was not possible to treat people like that when playing go and it would be shameful to let his opponent win just because he was a senior minister. And if he was a good official, surely he would feel sorry for a child. Ye saw that Guo's skill was supreme and that he was morally upright and completely virtuous. He therefore invited him to go to Beijing, China with him. Guo's education was not yet complete and so the offer was declined, but his fame spread until the nobles in Beijing heard of him (this was in the Wanli era 1573~1620) and he was finally prevailed on to go there. There was a senior guoshou, one of the most famous in Beijing, called Lin Fuqing, who looked down on the young Guo. One day, in the presence of some nobles, Lin challenged Guo, saying, "Since you came to Beijing I still have not played you. I would like to play you today. It would give everyone the greatest pleasure." The nobles were overjoyed and offered silver as a prize for the winner. Guo several times declined. Lin thought he was afraid and became all the more haughty, so that eventually Guo had no option but to play. Lin then lost three games in a row, to his great embarrassment. The nobles heaped even more praise on Guo. Therefore his fame spread throughout the empire and famous players came from all four corners to challenge him. He played them one by one and beat them all. In the "Wuxi-xian Zhi" (History of Wuxi County) it is written: "When Guo opened the gates and let the enemy in, no-one dared look up at him. And so for several decades all go players regarded Guo Bailing of Wuxi as their paragon." Apart from the _[_Guanzi Pu_]_ he wrote a manual on four-stone games. He lived to over eighty and games survive with Zhou Lanyu, Sheng Dayou and Wang Hannian. The reading Guo Boling would be more appropriate for some versions of his name.

note: Descendant of Guo Bailing. Learnt go from his father, a scholar who ran a bookshop and spent his leisure time on go. By age 13 he was already supreme in his district and was banned by opponents from watching his father's games in case he gave help. In 1926 he went to Shanghai, China to seek out stronger players, especially the famous local master Wu Xianglin. But within a year he was the top player south of the Yangzi River, so in 1927 he went to Beijing, China and sought the help of Gu Shuiru. He also played the young Go Seigen on B-2 handicap - he never rose above this level even later against Japanese 9ds. After two years in Wuhan he returned to Shanghai in 1933 and associated with Duan Qirui, returning to Beijing (then known as Beiping) in 1936 and forming a go society with friends in Zhongshan Park. The phrase Nan Liu Bei Guo (Liu Dihuai The phrase Nan Liu Bei Guo (Liu Dihuai [champion] in the south, Guo in the North) was often used. He remained in Beijing until the war but settled in Shanghai in 1951, where he helped promote Chinese go with Vice Premier Chen Yi, through whom he also discussed go with Mao Zedong and Zhou Enlai. He became President of the Hoensha (amid controversy because of his low grade) in the summer of 1920, and 7d (also controversial - said to be administrative) in 1921-01. He split his time between teaching go and composing haiku. status: The first head of the Edo-period Honinbo family in Japan.
career: As the top player of his time (equivalent to low-dan professional today), he was summoned to court to play the shoguns Oda Nobunaga (1578), who, an unreliable legend has it, admiringly called him the first Meijin, and Hideyoshi (1583), who gave him official patronage in 1589, whereupon he took the name Sansa. He was appointed Gon no Daisozu (vice-archbishop) by Emperor Goyozei (1592). He won the first go tournament in 1603 and formally took name the Honinbo Sansa under Tokugawa Ieyasu in 1605. He was appointed godokoro 碁所 (highest go office), shogidokoro 将棋所 (highest shogi office) and hoin 法印 (the highest Buddhist rank, by which he is often simply referred to in go texts) in 1612.
name: Honinbo Sansa
note: Originally Kano Yosaburo 加纳与三郎. He was apprenticed to Nichien, chief priest of Jakkoji temple in Kyoto, around 1565 and a year later he took the Buddhist name Nikkai 日海, although he was also known by the name of one of the templets within the Jakkoji where he lived. This was the Honinbo. Some Japanese read Sansa as Sansha. He apparently appointed Sanseki as his heir but Sanseki appears to have pre-deceased him. He played the Korean Yi Yak-sa c. 1620. Only 34 games remain. He was one of the first four members of the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame inducted in 2004.
title: NA

status: 2nd head of the Edo-period Honinbo family in Japan.

Sansa left Sanetsu in the stewardship of Nakamura Doseki with instructions that he should succeed if good enough. He became head and 7d in 1631. He was forced, as 8d, by the Shogunate officials to play Yasui II (Yasui Sanchi) for the Meijinship (the first challenge match in history, 1645~1653) but an inconclusive result denied him the appointment.

title: NA

status: 3rd head of the Edo-period Honinbo family in Japan.
career: He became heir in 1658 and 7d in 1666. He later reached 8d. He played 20 games of a scheduled 60-game challenge match with Yasui II (Yasui Sanchi) 1668~1675 (to object, at the risk of exile if he lost, to Sanchi's elevation to Meijin). He beat Sanchi down from -B- to B-W-B. He played Castle Games from 1660 to 1675, ceding the headship to Dosaku in 1677. He fully retired in 1686.
name: Honinbo Doetsu
note: Original surname Niwa 丹羽. He was the first to formalise the dimensions of go boards, with Itagaki Yusen, and was the longest lived historical go player. He sometimes appears in game records under his Buddhist name Nissho.
title: NA

status: 4th head of the Edo-period Honinbo family in Japan.
career: He learnt go at 7. He succeeded as Honinbo head in 1677 upon Doetsu's retirement and at the same time an application was submitted for him to become Godokoro, which he did on 1678-06-03 (lunar 1678-IV-14). He was so eminent that, unusually, his accession was unchallenged. He famously represented the Shogun in this capacity when the Ryukyuan Peichin of Hamahiga visited in 1682.
name: Honinbo Dosaku
note: Originally Yamasaki Sanjiro 山崎三次郎 (the reading Yamasaki is on the authority of Nakayama Noriyuki who has done research for a book on Dosaku, but there are modern descendants of the family in the Shimane area who apparently use the Yamazaki reading). He attracted a constellation of great pupils. Most died young, but on his deathbed he appointed Kamiya Dochi as his heir and asked Inoue Dosetsu to take him under his wing until he was old enough. Dosaku is regarded as one of the greatest players ever, especially esteemed by pros not just because of his eminence but because of his contributions to go theory, and he is the one player who is unequivocally accorded the status of Go Sage (gosei). He was the brother of Inoue II. First member of the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame in 2004.
gostyle: Regarded by some as the inventor of fuseki as a theory - he made the go board wider by using larger "spider's web" extensions. Considered to be the examplar of making sabaki. He is also considered the first player to properly discover overconcentration. On the downside he was sometimes too fond of fancy moves, which sometimes turn into overplays. Dynamic and active.

status: 12th head of the Edo-period Honinbo family in Japan.
career: There is a newly discovered game that shows him as 1d in 1802, but previously he first came to notice as a pupil of Genjo around 1807, as 2d. He was appointed Genjo's heir in 1819 (as 7d), he took over as Honinbo XII in 1827 and became 8d in 1828. He was made Meijin-Godokoro in 1831 after heavy politicking, which led to retraction of his appointment and retirement in 1838. He played Castle Games from 1819.
name: Honinbo Jowa
note: Originally surnamed Toya 戸谷 (which some read as Todani), though this does not appear in any game records, then Kadono Matsunosuke 葛野松之助, then Kadono Jowa 葛野丈和. Kadono was the long accepted reading of 葛野 (as also for Kuzuno Chuzaemon, Kuzuno Dowa and Kuzuno Kamesaburo). There is, however, recent research that shows that the correct reading is Kuzuno. In general, his origins and early history (there are virtually no early games) are shrouded im mystery, surprisingly so, and this has led to the suggestion that Jowa himself blotted out details of his early life to avoid embarrassment. He was, however, the son of an itinerant merchant who eventually settled him in Edo. Until the emergence of Honinbo Shusaku he was classed with Dosaku as a Go Sage, and his rivalry with Inoue Genan Inseki to become Meijin has become legendary - though both are classed as of Meijin standard, both also attracted disapproval for their politicking. They sniped at each other through their go books, yet had the highest regard for each other's go. He was the father of Inoue Setsuzan Inseki and Nakagawa Kamesaburo I, and Hanako, wife of Shusaku. He was inducted into Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame in 2005.

status: 14th head of the Edo-period Honinbo family in Japan.
career: Learnt go in 1827. Jumped straight to 3d in 1834, 4d, 1835, 5d 1836, 6d 1838, 7d 1840, 8d 1849. Appointed heir to Josaku in 1840-IV, he blocked the accession of Inoue Genan Inseki as Meijin-Godokoro through a challenge match in that year. He succeeded as Honinbo XIV in 1847-XII. Having submitted an unsuccessful request for Meijin-Godokoro 1859 - it was opposed by the Inoue family - and hampered by the uncertain political climate, he suffered economically during the Meiji Restoration, in particular when his house burnt down. Father of Honinbo XV (Shuetsu), Honinbo XVI (Shugen) and Honinbo XVII (Shuei). His fourth son, Denkichi, became a merchant. He also had a daughter. He played Castle games 1840~1862.
name: Honinbo Shuwa
note: Originally Tsuchiya Toshihira (or Shunpei) and later Tsunetaro. He took the name Shuwa after shaving his head in 1832. He was inducted into the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame in 2005.
gostyle: Cho Chikun: "Shuwa's go is fast-paced and he has an excellent grasp of the overall position. He keeps forging ahead, beating his opponent to the big points. His go is also flexible. If he makes even a slight gain with a forcing move, he will stop worrying about that area and may then play from the opposite side. When it is time to sacrifice, he does without dilly-dallying, then looks elsewhere to start a fight.

title: NA

status: 16th and 20th heads of the Edo-period Honinbo family in Japan.
career: Became Honinbo XVI (as 3d, while his elder brother Shuei was in mourning) in 1879 because of the illness of Shuetsu. Retired in 1884 (as 4d), ceding the title to Shuei but resuming it as Honinbo XX when Shuei died. Despite a frivolous attitude, he was considered to be really 6d and, when criticised for succeeding as a mere 4d, he promoted himself to 6d for one day.
name: Honinbo Shugen
note: Third child of Honinbo XIV (Shuwa) and originally Tsuchiya Momosaburo 土屋百三郎 and later Tsuchiya Shugen 土屋秀元. He was the brother of Honinbo XV (Shuetsu) and Honinbo XVII (Shuei). Nicknamed Shusen (Rice-wine wizard) because of his love of drinking, which he even indulged during a game. He was a notoriously quick player and was even said to be fond of the difficult taisha opening because it led to early finishes and so left him more time to drink, often with his fellow tippler Nakagawa Senji. His brother Shuei disapproved. Grandfather of Tsuchiya Hanshichi.
title: NA

status: 18th head of the Edo-period Honinbo family in Japan.
career: 1d at age 11 and 3d 1853, at which point he became a full-time pupil and began studying with great diligence. 5d 1861, 6d 1861 (taking the name Murase Shuho). He was recommended as heir to Shuwa in 1862 when Shusaku died - he had been ranked with Shusaku as one of the "two jewels" of the Honinbo household - but was opposed by the widow of Honinbo Jowa. Shuetsu, Shuwa's son, was chosen instead, but Shuho was compensated by being made 7d, and so eligible to appear in Castle Games, in 1864. He shaved his head in readiness, but it was turbulent times for the Shogunate and the invitation to play never came. With the routes to preferment within the Honinbo family apparently blocked off, he went travelling, a course that annoyed some Honinbo family members. Co-founder and first head of the Hoensha in 1879-04. 8d 1881. He was ceded headship of the reconciled Honinbo family by Shuei in 1886 and died three months later. Teacher of Oskar Korschelt.
name: Honinbo Shuho
note: Originally Murase Yakichi 村瀬彌吉, son of a carpenter. He learnt go by watching the games of the father of a policeman he became friendly with. He began visiting the Honinbo school, which was nearby in Kurumazaka, at age 8 and both Jowa and Shuwa spotted and nurtured his talent early on. The boy's family was poor and could barely afford even seasonal gifts to the Honinbo school, but Shuwa insisted to the father that that was no impediment - Yakichi was "not part of a mere flock of sparrows." This made Shuho have even more of a sense of obligation to his teacher than would normally be expected. He was inducted into the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame in 2007.

name: Hu Peiquan
note: He was 12 by the Oriental count in Shanghai, China, in 1931 when he played Masubuchi Tatusko on 3 stones. It appears he is the person described as a "mechanics educator": Hu Peiquan, Engineering Mechanics, educator, early years engaged in aeronautical research work in the United States, returning home after more than 40 years and long-term committed to mechanics education. Since childhood, intelligent and eager to learn. The 16-year-old was admitted to St. John's University Department of Civil Engineering, Shanghai, graduating as a 20-year-old and receiving a bachelor's degree in civil engineering. He went soon to the United States to the University of Michigan to study civil engineering, receiving a Master of Science degree as a 21-year-old, and as a 24-year-old a Ph.D. in engineering mechanics. In April 1948, Shanghai players Hu Peiquan, Yu Shichun issued the monthly "Go Communications, but it ceased publication on the liberation of Shanghai in May 1949. In 1961 the Urban Chess Sports Association was founded. The following year, Xie Chenda and Hu Peiquan were elected members of the China Weiqi Association with Wang Youchen of Shanghai and Huang Chengchen of Chengdu.

career: He made a fortune in textiles, chemicals and food products after moving to Taiwan after World War II. He was also deputy head of the Bank of Taiwan and Chairman of the International Securities and Credit Corporation. He passed part of his fortune to go through the Ing Chang-ki Weichi Educational Foundation instituted in 1972 in Taiwan.
name: Ing Chang-ki
note: His particular passion was reforming the rules of go into a logical whole, and in pursuit of this he invented his own go board and go clock, and sponsored tournaments which were required to use the large komi of 8 points he believed was justified by statistics. He died aged 83. His son Ying Minghao took over some of his go promotion, but in China itself his legacy is the Ing Weiqi Foundation in Shanghai, China. His son Ing Minghao 應明皓 (died 2019-04-20, aged 76) continued his support for go as President of the Ing Group.

status: Japanese player and 3rd head of the Inoue family from 1697.

career: Dosaku made him 8d in 1702 but had him promise not to seek the post of Meijin-godokoro and instead to act as guardian to the new Honinbo heir and Dosaku's Meijin-designate, Dochi. But he did become Meijin in 1710 to overcome the protocol problem of awarding diplomas to visiting Ryukyuans, though he desisted from taking office as godokoro in deference to Dosaku's wishes. Once installed as Meijin, he refused to give it up, which led to animosity with the Honinbo family. He played Castle Games from 1697.
name: Inoue Dosetsu Inseki
note: Originally Kuwabara Dosetsu 桑原道節, he is often referred to as Meijin Inseki 名人因碩 or Meijin Inoue Inseki 名人井上因碩, being the only Inoue to become Meijin. Author of _[_Igo Hatsuyoron_]_ (On the Development of Tactical Strength in Go).

status: Japanese player who was the 9th head of the Inoue family.
career: Under Intatsu, Inoue VIII, he took the name Insai　因済, later Inzui 因随, and eventually Insa. On the death of Inoue VII, he left Edo to serve the Mizuno family in Karatsu, Kyushu, but returned on death of Inoue VIII to become Inoue Insa Inseki on lunar 1810-XII-4 (1810-12-29), as 5d. He later reached 6d. He was a little behind Honinbo Genjo. At Black his score was 3-3-2 plus 4 left unfinished (he also left 18 games at B-2 against Genjo). Castle games from 1811. He retired in 1824.

status: Japanese player who joined Hoensha as schoolboy in 1895, where he became a pupil of Iwasaki Kenzo.
career: He left the Hoensha to attend university and flirted with a literary career, but then joined the school of Honinbo Shuei. At the time he was the only graduate go professional. 1d 1900, and 2d from Hoensha, but styled himself 3d and toured the Kansai. He returned to Tokyo in 1908, joined the Honinbo school again and was made 3d by Honinbo Shugen. 4d 1912, 5d 1919. As the best educated go player of his time, his literary talents were called on extensively to promote go in the burgeoning press. He was a ghost writer for Honinbo Shusai but his writings elsewhere provoked Shusai, who took the opportunity of finding fault with the Inoue school to expel Inoue Kohei (even though unrelated) from the Honinbo school. He therefore refused to join the Nihon Ki-in, but was awarded 6d by them just before his death in 1941.
name: Inoue Kohei

career: As a member of the Kiseisha, he scored a notable run of 10 straight wins in a Miyako Shinbun tournament, and celebrated by drinking 100 bottles of beer over two days and three nights. He was awarded 5d for his Miyako Shinbun achievement, but when he later transferred to the Keiinsha, he was the first to suffer a demotion (to 4d) as the result of a more rigorous grading policy. He returned to Miyazaki in 1943 to teach go and never went back to the mainstream.

career: He learnt go very young and on a visit by Honinbo Shuwa he was able to play him on 3 stones. He originally frequented the Hayashi house, but when the Inoue headship became vacant after a murder by Inoue XII, the authorities were persuaded by the daimyo to let his retainer take over in 1850. In 1859 he opposed Shuwa's application for Godokoro on the strength of having beaten him by 1 point with Black in a masterpiece game. He joined Hoensha in 1879 but was later forced out by the Honinbo family. In 1882 he awarded himself 7d without the approval of the other schools. He died on tour in Kobe without appointing an heir. He played Castle Games from 1850 to 1860 (the last by an Inoue).

status: Japanese player who was the 12th head of the Inoue family.
career: From 1d to 4d he moved in step with Honinbo Shuwa, but he was then afflicted by an eye disease which kept him from the go board. In 1843 he was adopted by Mizutani Takujun, taking the name Mizutani Junsaku 水谷順策. He was later adopted and appointed as heir by Inoue XI around 1845, and he took the name Inoue Shutetsu 井上秀徹. He succeeded as Inoue XII in 1848 (as 6d). In 1849, when mentally disturbed, he killed a pupil, Shimazaki Renzaburo. Mortified, he retired under the name Inoue Setsuzan Inseki. Castle games from lunar 1846 (as Inoue Shutetsu).
name: Inoue Setsuzan Inseki

status: Japanese player who was the 5th head of the Inoue family.
career: He became the Inoue heir in 1726 (as 6d) and succeeded to the headship in 1734. 7d 1735. In 1737 he was embroiled in an argument with the shogi families over precedence. From 1739 to 1742 he was also involved in disputes over grading since he coveted the vacant Meijinship for himself. In 1748 a visit by Ryukyuans caused problems of protocol - they had previously been able to play Meijins but now there was none. Shunseki signed the requisite diplomas, styling himself Japanese champion. 8d 1764. In 1766 he lost a challenge match for the Meijinship. His fortunes were devastated by a fire in 1769. He retired in 1772. He played Castle Games from 1726.
name: Inoue Shunseki Inseki

status: Japanese professional with the Hoensha, Nihon Ki-in
teacher: He was a live-in pupil of Hirose Keijiro while also studying at the Hoensha (from 1907).
career: Learnt go in 1903 by watching his father. 1d 1908-02, 2d 1911, 3d 1913, 4d 1916, 5d 1919, 6d 1921. He became vice-president of the Hoensha in 1923, and joined the Nihon Ki-in 1924, but he spent a brief time with the Kiseisha, returning to the Ki-in in 1927 through the intervention of patrons. 7d (first in the Nihon Ki-in Oteai) 1932-02 (earned in 1931). He bested Suzuki Tamejiro and Segoe Kensaku in a "Three 7ds" tournament for Jiji Shinpo in 1932. He was entitled to 8d (again the first in the Oteai) in 1939 through winning a game defaulted by his opponent, Suzuki Tamejiro 7d, who was older and feigned sickness to avoid seeing Kato promoted. But Kato rejected it (though he did go through the nigiri procedure, was given White and then the game; apparently, though, the game was eventually played and Kato lost) until he earned it fully (by one account; _[_Kido_]_ says this too was a recommendation by all the top dan players for many years of meritorious service) in 1942-03. Suzuki was then given 8d by recommendation at the same time (though Iwamoto says he did not become 8d till 1943 - presumably the date of the ceremony). His later career was impaired as he was afflicted by chronic rheumatism from 1941.
name: Kato Shin
note: He was nicknamed the 黒甲將軍 (Black-armoured General) because of his style. He was the brother of Tanaka Minaichi.

teacher: Torii Nabejiro (1917), Kubomatsu Katsukiyo (from 1918) and Suzuki Tamejiro (from 1921).
career: 1d 1924, 2d 1926, 3d 1926, 4d 1927. In that year he won eight games in a row for the Nihon Ki-in in match against Kiseisha, earning the nickname 怪童丸 (_[_Kaidomaru_]_ = Wonder Kid). 5d 1930. In 1938, while experimenting, he lost all his games in the Spring Oteai (a record). In 1933 he played six games of a 10-game match with Go Seigen, with the first appearance of their joint New Fuseki. 6d 1934, 7d 1936. In 1938 played the game featured in Kawabata Yasunari's novel Meijin to mark the retirement of Honinbo Shusai. From 1939-09 to 1941-06 he played and lost the "Kamakura" 10-game match with Go Seigen. He visited Taiwan in 1940. 8d 1942-09 (together with Go Seigen). In 1942-10 he visited North China and Manchuria. He took a one-year lay-off in 1954 and retired from the Oteai because of a stroke - blood circulation problems had punctuated his earlier career. 9d 1956. Throughout his career he had taken a large number of live-in pupils at his home in Hiratsuka, but in 1961 he opened the Kitani Dojo school instead in Tokyo, Japan. 1962 saw a celebration to mark the first combined 100d total of his pupils, but by 1970 his pupils' grades had reached a total of 200 dan. In 1964 further illness prompted almost total retirement and in 1974 he closed his school.
name: Kitani Minoru
note: Husband of Kitani Miharu, father of Kobayashi Reiko, father-in-law of Kobayashi Koichi, grandfather of Kobayashi Izumi, and great grandfather Cho Kosumi. His collected games include games against his children apart from Reiko, namely Nobuko and Masamichi who were of very strong amateur standard. He was notorious as a slow player and in the Oteai he invariably used his time up by about move 100 but was able to play the rest of the game accurately at a minute a move. He was awarded the Medal of Honour with Purple Ribbon in 1965 and the Junior 4th Class of the Order of the Sacred Treasure on his death in 1975. He was inducted into the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame in 2010. Some Japanese read his name as Kidani.
runnerup: 4th Honinbo (1947), 1st Honinbos & 8-dans (1952), 8th Honinbo (1953), 2nd Tokyo Shinbun (1957), 5th NK Championship (1958), 5th NHK (1958), 14th Honinbo (1959), 4th Saikoi (1959), 2nd Nihon Saikyo (1959), 8th NHK (1961)
winner: 1929 Spring Oteai A, 1950 Spring Oteai A, 1st Tokyo Shinbun (1956), 2nd Saikoi (1957), 3rd Saikoi (1958), 7th NHK (1960)
gostyle: Had the most startling changes of style of any player. Originally a powerful fighter then, as a co-founder of New Fuseki, he emphasised the centre. Shortly after, he switched to favouring territory and like most things did this to extremes. Ultra-stubborn. He did not like knight's moves.

His extant games total just over 110 and his winning ratio there was around 90%. He was struck down by typhoid fever and was given a 6d diploma dated 1924-01-05 on his deathbed.
name: Kogishi Soji
note: His early death is said to have prompted Shusai to surrender the hereditary Honinbo title. Kogishi is definitely correct according to pupil Masubuchi Tatsuko, but the reading Ogishi has been widely used in the go world and appears in the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame (though he is not yet a member).

born: Jiyang Village, Duchang County, Jiangxi Province, China
status: Famous as the premier player in the time of the Northern Song emperors Shen Zong (r. 1068~1086) and Zhe Zong (r. 1086~1101).
career: When the court invited applications for a position as imperial go tutor, he went to the capital, where he was successful and remained top player for two decades.
name: Liu Zhongfu
note: Styled Fuzhi. His journey to the capital features in a famous go story, part of which is based on astounding an audience in Qiantang (modern Hangzhou) by replaying a dozen or so games from memory. On the first day he laid out some goods of value and offered to play all-comers with these as a stake. By the next day news of his skill had reached the noted players of the area and he was invited to play, for a stake, in the Purple Clouds palace in the north of the city. The best player was chosen as his opponent and Liu took White and ceded him first move. By move 50 the onlookers were convinced White was losing, and his opponent declared Black had won. But Liu disagreed and 20 moves later began to sweep the stones off the board. His opponent angrily assumed he was trying to cover up his loss, but Liu smiled and said there were no strong players in Qiantang. He first began to play over ten or so games he had played the previous day, pointing out his opponents' errors. Then he began to replay faultlessly that day's unfinished game. He then said White needed just one move to ensure victory by at least 10 points. If anyone could find the move, he would give up and return home. No-one found it. He showed his move and said it would be effective 20 moves from now. Still no-one understood. Liu then proposed restarting the game. 20 moves later the position had changed drastically in White's favour, and when the game was completed he had won by 13 points. The onlookers gasped in admiration and Liu continued on to the capital. His reign there lasted some 20 years. He made important contributions to go theory, particularly through his still extant _[_Qi Jue_]_ (Go Secrets), drawing on Wang Jixin's _[_Ten Precepts_]_. He gives an overall and high-level exposition of go theory based on the four concepts of fuseki, invasion/attack, tactics and profit/loss.
gostyle: His own style was fierce and swift attack with dozens of brilliant moves. His game with Lishan Lao Ao is famous and apparently exemplifies his style.

career: In Spring 1934, at age 35, he was allowed 2d in the B Section of the Nihon Ki-in, whereupon he took the professional name Miyake Sokuryu 三宅速隆. In 1936 he moved to Kobe and was a pillar of go there, and he mixed with the likes of Kubomatsu Katsukiyo. The war, including death of both parents, frustrated his desire to play go professionally, so at age 41 he retired as a pro and reverted to his original name.

status: Japanese player loosely associated with the Honinbo school, and later a Hoensha member.
career: He showed prodigious talent as a youngster, and Honinbo Shusaku wanted him as his pupil, but parental opposition meant he never left Shikoku (where he worked as a primary school teacher) or had a go mentor until he was 34. He joined the Hoensha (where, with Kobayashi Tetsujiro, Sakai Yasujiro and Takahashi Kinesaburo, he was one of the Hoensha Four Heavenly Kings) as +4d in 1880. 5d 1881, 6d 1882. This was the top level in the Hoensha after Honinbo Shuho, and Shuho wanted to promote him to 7d as he was the only player to get as near as -BBW- handicap to him. All the Hoensha members agreed except Takahashi, who insisted on a 10-game match. Mizutani won the match but stonewalling by Takahashi delayed the promotion, and 10 days after the match Mizutani died of tuberculosis. He was awarded 7d posthumously.
name: Mizutani Nuiji
note: His reputation after his death was slightly attenuated because it was felt his game showed traces of his youth spent playing gambling go, where it was necessary to win by as big a margin as possible. In the murky period after the end of the Shogunate, when details of his life are sketchy, it is believed he spent time as an unsuccessful gambler in the yakuza world, ending up burdened with several loans. It seems he also thought then about becoming a doctor. He was also noted for a haughty attitude and for being a slow player, especially at unexpected moments. He was once attacked at night by yakuza with knives after he had won a huge sum at gambling go. He resisted with bare hands and escaped, but when he died it was discovered in his coffin that he had 28 scars on his head alone, his body was equally scarred, and he had few complete fingers.

status: Chinese professional with the Chinese Go Association.
career: He was awarded immediate 9d in 1982 as soon as China adopted professional grades. He was brought up in Beijing, China and came to prominence when he won a youth tournament there in 1963 after learning go at age 9. He won the 1st World Amateur title in 1976. He had been groomed by the Chinese Communist Party, through the personal intervention of Chen Yi, as a likely player to surpass the Japanese, but he was fortunate too in receiving help from Japan through Fujisawa Hideyuki. The Party helped him as a youngster by having the veteran master Guo Tisheng move in with the Nie family but at age 19 he suffered badly during the Cultural Revolution, when he was sent to a farm in Shanke, Heilongjiang, on the Soviet border. He kept his go alive by playing over games in his head. He studied old Chinese games and copies of Japanese Kido Yearbooks. He was allowed to return to Beijing in 1972 where he was admitted to the national training squad and started studying under Chen Zude. His defeat of the Japanese 9d Miyamoto Naoki soon after was the turning point in his career and made him nationally famous. He has suffered from a heart condition, exacerbated by the farm work, that forces him to take oxygen during a game. He was given the lifetime honorific title Go Sage (Qisheng) by the Chinese Weiqi Association in 1988-07.
name: Nie Weiping
note: He was the first Chinese professional with the Chinese Go Association to be feared as an equal by the Japanese, against whom his staunch defence in China-Japan matches earned him the nickname Iron Goalkeeper. Other nicknames were Whirlwind Nie and Mister Three Ears (from the old version of the character with which his name is written). Former husband of Kong Xiangming and father of Ko Reibun, and so related by marriage to Kobayashi Satoru. He is also noted as a bridge player, and was once a partner of Deng Xiaoping.

status: Japanese player of samurai stock through the Matsudaira clan.
career: He learnt go at about age 5 from his father. After that he was virtually self taught and when he became a pupil of Honinbo Shuei, he was allowed after six months to jump straight to 2d in 1903. 3d 1904, 4d 1909, 5d 1914. He attracted opprobrium by writing _[_Hyo no hyo_]_　評の評 ("Commentaries on the commentaries") of Honinbo Shusai and Nakagawa Kamesaburo in the journal _[_Tora no Maki_]_ 虎の巻. Unabashed, he started the journal _[_Igo Hyoron_]_ 囲碁評論 with the same column in 1918. He was censured and then expelled by the house of Honinbo and by the Hoensha in 1918-12, but a reconciliation was effected with Shusai in 1923 after _[_Igo Hyoron_]_ was halted by the Great Kanto earthquake. When living in Kobe, he was called on by the Kiseisha to represent them in 1926 in their match with the Nihon Ki-in, for which he was made 6d. In 1927 he began in a famous _[_Yomiuri Shinbun_]_-sponsored 10-game match with Suzuki Tamejiro 7d, for which he was promoted to 7d (being ahead of Suzuki in games between them). He died of tuberculosis and because of that illness the players played in separate rooms. The score was 5-2-2 to Suzuki when the match was called off after Nozawa's condition deteriorated in 1930-03.
name: Nozawa Chikucho
note: In his successful 3d and 4d period he was nicknamed 常勝将軍軍 (Ever-victorious General) and 鬼将軍 (Demon General).

career: He was the House of Representatives member for Akita City for two terms, then a businessman. He was given an honorary 5d by both Hoensha and the Honinbos in the Taisho era, which is when he was especially active as a patron. He once set up a series of games with high-dan players, including Shusai on 2 stones but the rest on Black, with a large prize of 50 yen per game (a university graduate then would have a starting salary of less than 40 yen). He did not do well but Iwasa Kei let him save face by contriving a jigo. Still, he was the strongest amateur of his time and even played Segoe Kensaku 6d on Black in 1925. When the Nihon Ki-in was formed he was given a 5d diploma, the only one ever given to an amateur until 1952 when a special tournament to create amateur 5ds was started.

career: Originally a member of the Hoensha from age 12 but he also frequented the Igo Doshikai. 1d 1914, 2d 1916, 3d 1918, 4d 1919, 5d 1920 (another source says 1921). He left the Hoensha in 1923 for the Hiseikai and the Chuo Ki-in, where, with Kogishi Soji and others, he published the journal _[_Kiin Shinpo_]_. 6d 1924. He left the Nihon Ki-in then for Kiseisha but returned in 1928. 7d 1942 (another source says 1939). Despite his rapid progress he did not really make his mark through being eclipsed by other young players such as Kogishi Soji who beat him down in a 10-game match. However, he did set a record for winning two successive Oteai sessions with perfect scores (Autumn 1942 and Spring 1943), and this contributed to a remarkable winning ratio just before he died. A famous incident in the Oteai occurred when he played a game that would decide whether he would be promoted to 7d (against a 4d identified only as K). K resigned but Onoda refused to accept it, saying the game was not yet decided. They continued till midnight whereupon it proved he had lost by a point. The next day he shaved his head in penance. Posthumous 8d.
name: Onoda Chiyotaro
note: He was unusual among go players then for having graduated from middle school. He was nicknamed Onida Chiyotaro 鬼田強太郎 (a play on hs surname, substituting 鬼 (devil) for 小野 and 強 (strong) for 千代. He was an ardent mountaineer.

status: Chinese professional with the Chinese Go Association.
career: Learnt go at age 6 and joined the national training squad at age 13. 4d 1982, 5d 1982, 6d 1983, Professional and 7d 1985, 8d 1986, 9d 1987. In 1988 he suffered an attack of a neurological condition which produced splitting headaches when he looked at go diagrams, and he took six months off, but came back in top form. He had the nickname Qianda (Big Qian), which did not refer here to being an elder son but to the prominent size of his head. It was assumed that his big brain was connected with his condition. After a glorious series of tournaments he reached the final of the 4th Fujitsu Cup in 1991, but then his medical problems returned and he had to default the game. He returned to Shanghai for hospital treatment and drug therapy which kept him away from go for most of a decade. He retired in 1996. In 2001 he was relieved of treatment but was still convalescing. His treatment costs were borne by the Chinese Go Association and there were hopes in 2002 that he might begin teaching, but his tournament career was certainly on hold. He resumed professional play in 2021.

status: Chinese-born professional at the Nihon Ki-in Main (Tokyo) Branch. Internationally has represented both Japan and Chinese Taipei.
career: His father was a graduate of Tokyo, Japan University and served as vice-consul of the pre-war Taiwanese government (then under Japanese rule). The family moved to mainland China to escape the war and he was born there, but from age 4 to 7 he lived in Taipei and from 7 to 10 in Taizhong (central Taiwan). He learnt go at 8 after watching his father, brother and sister play (his mother had died when he was 5). He was about amateur 4d when Go Seigen gave him a trial game on a visit to Taiwan in 1952 and accepted him as a pupil. He transferred to Kyoto Prefecture, Japan, Japan, where he had relatives, in 1952. When the relatives moved, he moved in with Fujita Goro. He became an insei at the Nihon Ki-in Tokyo branch in 1953, but switched to the Kansai (Osaka) Branch the following year. 1d 1955, 2d 1955 (his father's death was kept from him till he made this grade), 3d 1957, 4d 1958, 5d 1959, 6d 1960 (and he then transferred back to the main branch of the Nihon Ki-in, also becoming the first teenaged 6d in the Nihon Ki-in), 7d 1962, 8d 1965, 9d 1967. then youngest ever Meijin, at age 23. The second player to record 1,000 wins in Japan, he was also second to reach 1,200 (2002-04-18) and first to reach 1300 (19 October 2006, at which stage his statictics were 1300-793-1-2). In 2004-03, during the 3rd CSK Cup, he became the first player to record 2,000 career games (of which he won 1,247 - also a record for total wins - with 1 jigo and 2 void games) ahead of Kato Masao on 1,891. His career record as of 2010-12-02 was 1363-840-1-2.

note: He was often referred to in tandem with Otake Hideo as Chikurin 竹林. Father of Rin Hiromi and Rin Yoshimi. He was awarded the Order of the Rising Sun, Gold Rays with Neck Ribbon (III), in 2017, having previously been given the Medal of Honour with Purple Ribbon in 2005.

status: Japanese professional in the Nihon Ki-in.
career: He learnt go at 5 from his grandfather Hikobee while recuperating from an eye illness and first met pros on holiday in Kobe in 1905, but he did not take go up seriously until he went to Tokyo after graduation in 1908. There he joined the Hoensha and beat Kobayashi Tetsutaro 3d on Black. Then he played trial games with Suzuki Tamejiro 3d in 1909 and was allowed to skip to +3d after winning 4-2. 4d 1912, 5d 1917. In 1919 he first visited Northern China. 6d 1921-02, 7d 1926-04 (by recommendation from the Nihon Ki-in), 8d 1942-03 (by recommendation). Retired with honorary 9d in 1955-01. He was a founder member of the Hiseikai in 1922 with Karigane Junichi, Suzuki Tamejiro and Takabe Dohei (one of its innovations was the use of time limits), but he was also one of the main promoters of the Nihon Ki-in and of unification of the go world in 1924. In the early Showa period he went back to China several times and there met Go Seigen, taking him as his pupil. A famous incident in 1928-10 involved him and Takahashi Toshimitsu in the Ten-Thousand Year Ko dispute. After the Pacific War (during which he was present at the Atom Bomb game), he was managing director of the Nihon Ki-in to 1948 and supervised its rebuilding. He was also active in spreading go overseas. He compiled two great game collections _[_O-shiro Gofu_]_ (Castle Games; 1950) and _[_Meiji Gofu_]_ (Games of the Meiji Era; 1959). One of his proudest achievements was having a star pupil from the three main go nations: Hashimoto Utaro (Japan), Go Seigen (China) and Cho Hun-hyeon (Korea). His efforts to spread go also include visits to Hawaii (1950) and Europe (1961). He received several government honours, including being awarded the Medal of Honour with Purple Ribbon in 1958 and being appointed to the Order of the Sacred Treasure, Gold and Silver Star, in 1966, with elevation to the Senior Fourth Rank in 1972. He was inducted into the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame as member No. 11 in September 2009.
name: Segoe Kensaku
note: For a time, when young, he used the 憲策 version above of his name out of admiration for Honinbo Shusaku who came from the same area. Many Japanese, even in the go world, incorrectly read his name Segoshi. His wife Iso died on 1964-08-11, aged 70.

status: A high-ranking samurai in the service of Lord Sanada Yukitaka of Matsushiro in Shinano (Nagano Prefecture), but also a significant go player.
career: He reached 1d in 1801, whereupon he returned home. But his military accomplishments were poor and his colleagues criticised him as not befitting a samurai. He therefore gave up go until he mastered the martial arts. In 1826 he returned to Edo to join Honinbo Genjo and then Jowa. His go ability blossomed and he shot up to 5d strength. But the Honinbo family refused to give diplomas for high grades to amateurs and offered him 3d. He declined it and stayed at 1d, though playing as a 5d. His 20-game match (taking -B-) with Honinbo Shusaku is celebrated. His later years were devoted to Zen and long travels. Of scholarly bent, he produced several go books.

status: One of the Chinese greats who famously enjoyed rivalry with his fellow townsman and fellow student Fan Xiping, who was just one year older and of rather different background.
career: His was an old and well known family that had enjoyed literary fame for generations. He was, however, a sickly child and showed little skill in ordinary studies, which is why he was allowed to play go. He was taken by his father to meet young Fan when his fame spread, and they were lost in admiration. Shi said in a book years later that he decided to emulate Fan then. Within a year he improved three stones and was almost on a par with Fan. Fan's teacher Yu Yongjia introduced Fan and Shi to the 78-year old guoshou Xu Xingyou, who played them on three stones. They were taken to other famous patrons as a pair but Shi then was always a slight step behind Fan (and he was a slow, dour player in contrast to the fast-moving Fan) and so they were not pitted against each other properly until their famous close match at Danghu Lake, which took place in 1739. These are the only games between them that remain. Shi and Fan's collected games form the famous _[_Haichang Er Miao Ji_]_ (Two Marvels from Haining). Shi spent his late years in Yangzhou, teaching go but to very few pupils. In this period, in 1762, he wrote _[_Yili Zhigui_]_ (Go Theory Expounded). Five years later he had his pupil Li Liang compile a continuation. Because this work was extremely hard, being written in rhymed verse with many technical terms, Qian Changze of the great Songjiang clan (a former patron and a strong amateur particularly known for his discussions of go theory) rendered it into a popular version, which is the version that became famous as _[_Yili Zhigui Tu_]_ (Illustrated Go Theory Expounded).
name: Shi Dingan
note: He was styled Shi Xiangxia 施襄夏.

status: Eldest son of Yasui I, whose name (as Yasui Santetsu 安井算哲) he bore at first but he changed it later to Shibukawa Sukezaemon Shunkai, and under this name he is better known as a scholar and astronomer.
career: In 1657, under the guardianship of Yasui Sanchi, he began to receive an official stipend and, after being appointed as the family heir in 1659, he began to play in Castle Games. According to Honinbo Dosaku he was 7d. He was also a distinguished Confucian scholar and the foremost expert of his time on astronomy, at which he became expert by studying the latest Chinese books based on imported European principles, and by making his own astronomical observations. A revised version of the calendar (the first by a Japanese) is due to him, at imperial request, and because of his involvement with this from 1683 he ceased playing Castle Games as Yasui Santetsu II. His new Jokyo era calendar was issued in 1684 and was used for 70 years. His reward was to be appointed by the shogunate to the Astronomical Institute (Tenmonkata) and in that capacity he changed his name to Shibukawa (the original name of the Yasui family) in 1702 and retired in lunar 1711-XII. He published many books on astronomy. His astronomy inspired a famous Castle Game against Dosaku in 1670 when he played first move on the centre point (tengen or the "origin of the heavens", but he lost by 9 points) and it is from this that tengen as a go term may have become popular.
name: Shibukawa Shunkai
note: Some Japanese read his name as Shibukawa Harumi. A book about him and his astronomy suggests this is actually the correct reading but it has not properly permeated the go world yet. He was inducted into the Nihon Ki-in Hall of Fame in 2012.

status: Japanese professional at the Nihon Ki-in Main (Tokyo) Branch.
teacher: Miyake Kazuo (1925) and Suzuki Tamejiro (from 1926-12-08), though he was probably more influenced by Suzuki's wife, Hideko.
career: He was a sickly child and was kept indoors a lot, so gravitated towards board games. 1d 1928 (one source has 1929 but that was when he first entered the Oteai), 2d 1930, 3d 1932, 4d 1934, 5d 1937, 6d 1942, 7d 1951, 8d 1954, 9d 1960. He was drafted into the army transport corps in 1937 and was sent to China in August in the wake of the Marco Polo Bridge Incident. After two years he was promoted to Private 1st Class but found it physically gruelling, and he was released from military service in 1939. He settled in Nagoya in 1950 about the time he became 7d, and began to blossom at go. But success in go brought more taxing games and obligatory parties (sometimes three a night). Alcohol did not agree with him and he tried to avoid it by dancing but it caught up with him and by 1958 he had an advanced duodenal ulcer. A doctor advised surgery. But a week after the operation he suffered severe haemorrhaging and had to be operated on again. A week later (November 1958) he insisted on playing Hosokawa Senjin in the 4th Saikoi and after 296 moves was on course to win and earn 9d. But at that point he fainted and could not continue. Carbon monoxide from the hand-warmer had caused a coronary thrombosis. For a time after that he defaulted many games, and he lost his places in the Honinbo and Saikoi leagues. This was when he changed the characters in his name from 利博 to 俊宏, to change his luck (it worked).The 俊広 version of his name was his latest and preferred one. He led a goodwill exchange to China in 1966 and opened his Shimamura Igo Club in Nagoya in 1967. He retired in 1973 (temporarily, after a stroke suffered during a game) and 1983. In 1977 he won the Tengen title and was then the eldest ever title holder. He was appointed to the Order of the Rising Sun, Gold Rays with Rosette, in 1982.
name: Shimamura Toshihiro
note: The 利博 version of the name has been read Shimamura Rihaku. Father of Shimamura Michihiro.

status: Businessman, member of the House of Representatives, and, as head of the _[_Yomiuri Shinbun_]_ newspaper, an important go sponsor.
career: He was a graduate of Tokyo University in 1911. He rose to head the Tokyo police force but resigned to take responsibility for the Toranomon Incident, and then became president of the _[_Yomiuri Shinbun_]_ in 1924. That paper was then in a slump, but he made it Japan's biggest newspaper. The gimmicks he used to boost circulation included: the Nihon Ki-in versus Keiinsha match (1926) which pitted Honinbo Shusai against Karigane Junichi in a long awaited grudge match; the introduction of professional baseball to Japan (Tokyo Giants in 1934, which later became Yomiuri Giants; he was the first inductee in Japan's baseball Hall of Fame); and the ten-game matches involving Go Seigen. He retained a go column even in the wartime tabloid editions. The Yomiuri's treatment of go was also innovative. Purged after the war, Shoriki re-established himself as president of Nippon Television Network and chairman of the Atomic Energy Commission. He was awarded honorary 7d by the Nihon Ki-in after the Yomiuri instituted the Meijin Tournament in 1960. He is esteemed also by judo fans (as the only non-professional 10th dan) and sumo fans.
name: Shoriki Matsutaro

She was the first and only pupil Kita had who was already skilled at go on entry to her school. 1d 1942, 2d 1944, 3d 1948, 4d 1949, 5d 1953 (1st woman to reach that grade in the Oteai, and ditto for all subsequent promotions), 6d 1956, 7d 1973, 8d 1983. She was mostly inactive for about 10 years from 1956 while raising a family.

note: Her maiden name was Honda Kazuko 本田寿子. She married Sugiuchi Masao in 1954. She is the sister of Honda Sachiko and Kusunoki Teruko. She was appointed to the Order of the Precious Crown, Wistaria (IV) in 1999. She is the oldest active professional and on 2018-10-04 became the oldest pro to win an official game, a record she has since extended. In April 2024 she became the oldest pro to compete in an official competition (against Morita Michihiro aged 97 years, 1 month and 5 days in the 51st Tengen).

status: Japanese player in the Nihon Ki-in.
career: She went to Korea with her father and learnt go from him at about 10. In 1911 she went to Tokyo to join the school of Kita Fumiko. She was regarded as the girls' equivalent prodigy of Kogishi Soji, though in fact she followed her teacher's experience and dressed, acted and spoke as a boy until she reached 1d in 1917. 2d 1920, 3d 1922, 4d 1932. She refused a 5d honorary diploma late in life on the grounds she had not earned 5d in play. She joined the Rikka-kai (a young players' study group) in 1930. When she married Suzuki Tamejiro in 1923 it was the first marriage between modern pros. She helped nurture his pupils such as Kitani, Sekiyama and Murashima, but separated from him (he complained she would stay up late studying instead of going to bed) and in her late years she was beset by financial problems. She sold her large house in Tokyo just before the end of the war, expecting to have to move to the country, only to discover that this was a bad move as the war ended soon after. These problems compounded bad nerves, and was killed when knocked over by an electric train at a crossing on the Central Line tram during a cloudburst (she did not see the tracks because of her umbrella). She had one pupil of her own, Kano Yoshinori.
name: Suzuki Hideko
note: Originally Taoka Fumiko, then Taoka Hideko 田岡秀子, she was born into a samurai family and niece of Iwasaki Kenzo. The change of name to Hideko came about because it was considered inconvenient when she became a live-in pupil of Kita Fumiko (even the characters were the same). The change was made by Kojima Kazuo, who helped her much also in later life.
