origin: Kariya Township (now a city), Hekikai District, Aichi Prefecture, Japan
status: Japanese professional with the Nihon Ki-in.
career: He learnt go at 11. He went to Tokyo at age 17 for further education, hoping to be a doctor, but decided on go as a career and so joined the Hoensha in 1902, also joining Iwasaki Kenzo as a pupil. He still graduated from middle school, at a time when only 2% of the population went to middle school. Through beating his teacher on two stones he was allowed to jump straight to 3d. He volunteered for the Nagoya Artillery Regiment in 1904 at the time of the Russo-Japanese War and served for one year. He then travelled for a couple  of years. Then he became a pupil of Honinbo Shuei as 3d. 4d 1912. His almost invincible record as Black at this time, even against Honinbo Shusai, and his achievement of winning 10 straight games in the _[_Yorozu Choho_]_ newspaper win & continue from 1914~18 earned him the nickname Asahi Shogun (General Rising Sun) 旭将軍. His ambitions led him to Singapore in 1916, after a visit to China, to manage a rubber plantation, but with the market failing he returned to Japan after 18 months. He called in on Kubomatsu Katsukiyo in the Kansai region. There he played Hashimoto Utaro on four stones and promised to be his teacher. However, the following year he returned to Singapore via Shanghai to settle his affairs at the rubber plantation, but again repatriated himself in 1921 after the market slumped. In the meantime Kubomatsu decided Hashimoto should go to Segoe Kensaku. He reached 6d in 1919 or 1921, depending on source. In 1922 he joined forces with Karigane Junichi, Segoe Kensaku and Takabe Dohei to form the Hiseikai. Like them he briefly supported the newly formed Nihon Ki-in in 1924 but soon left, for the Kiseisha, returning after about 18 months. The Nihon Ki-in promoted him by recommendation to 7d in 1926-04 when he rejoined (he was their oldest player), but part of the deal was that from 1927 he should play a 10-game match with Nozawa Chikucho 7d. He was leading 5-2-2 before Nozawa retired through ill health in 1930. Around this time Suzuki benefited from the patronage of Kagami Kenkichi. He reached 8d in 1942-03 (by recommendation - see also under Kato Shin), and was made honorary 9d 1957. He was one of the most prolific go writers and is known principally for his gigantic opus the _[_Igo Daijiten_]_ (a joseki dictionary which incorporates his students' work) of 1935. He famously made the comment "too ambitious" on 3. Q4 after 1. Q16, 2. D17 in the first game of the first Honinbo Tournament. He played in the first radio game in 1933-01 with Mitsuhara Itaro. He received the Medal of Honour with Purple Ribbon in 1960 in the month he died.
name: Suzuki Tamejiro

status: Japanese professional prominent in several organisations prior to the Nihon Ki-in, and also in Sino-Japanese go.
career: He learnt go at 16 and in 1899 joined the Hoensha as a student for a while, but then went touring in Kyushu before returning to the Hoensha in 1901. Smitten by Wanderlust he was rarely in one place for any length of time. His skill improved considerably between 1901 and 1903 when he played several matches with Inoue XV and Takasaki Taisaku. He joined Honinbo Shuei in 1903 (at the instigation of Tamura Yasuhisa, the future Honinbo Shusai) and was given his first diploma, as 4d at age 22. Then he studied a great deal with Nozawa Chikucho. After Shuei's death he supported Shusai in the Honinbo succession row. He helped found the Igo Doshikai in 1909-05 and played there till July. In August he set off for Korea, then in 1912 went to Northern China and Manchuria, where he helped spread go. He returned to Japan in 1915. The Chinese book _[_Wenqiu Yinshe Yipu_]_ is a collection of his games, giving handicaps, in China against some distinguished personages and top players. One of his pet ideas was the formation of a Japan-China Go Association. 5d 1912, 6d 1918/21. A founder of the Hiseikai in 1922, he also took part in the formation of the Nihon Ki-in in 1924, but soon left to help set up the Kiseisha and so was one of the major contestants in the famous Insha match between the Nihon Ki-in and the Kiseisha. 7d 1929. He started publishing a journal called _[_Go_]_ in 1930. 8d 1933-11 (from the Kiseisha, together with Karigane Junichi). He broke with Karigane in 1941 after resisting calls for reform of the Kiseisha. Karigane and the other members then set up the Keiinsha.

status: Japanese player in the Honinbo school and then the Hoensha.
career: He was originally a pupil of Honinbo Shuwa with whom he reached 5d, but later he joined the Hoensha where he was to become famous for his obstinacy that led to one of the greatest grudge matches of all time with Mizutani Nuiji in 1884. Mizutani was generally acknowledged ready for promotion but Takahashi pointed out he was one game ahead against him in their private series and so refused to acquiesce. His obstinacy was acknowledged to come from high principles. When Honinbo Shuei awarded a diploma to his profligate brother Shugen, Takahashi sent back his 5d diploma. A famous joke in the go world was that when Shuei was at his inauguration ceremony for 8d, he formally announced that if anyone objected they should speak up now. Takahashi piped up and said if he was 10 years younger he would have challenged him. He reached 6d in 1901.

status: Japanese player in the Inoue school.
career: He learnt go at age 8 from an uncle and in the same year was able to play Kawase Takanosuke, a 5d, on 9 stones. A month later he became a pupil of the Inoue family under Fujita Keisai 3d, with whom he spent about two years. He was noted as a very diligent student in this period, working from dawn to bedtime at household tasks, playing guests and studying games - he averaged about 2,800 games a year, including 250 with his teacher, progressing from 8 stones to Black. 1d 1855. In 1859 he played a 10-game match with Honinbo Shuho on 2 and 3 stones, scoring level. He said he benefited enormously from Shuho's kind comments. From 1859 to 1864 he toured the Kyoto Prefecture, Japan area as a player. He went to Tokyo, Japan in 1872 to test his go skill and became a member of the Hoensha. After excellent results against the top players he asked to be promoted to 5d. This was rejected as unconventional. Partly because of this he felt insecure about his future and left go completely for eight years to work as a civil servant. He returned to Hoensha in 1879. In 1883, through the intervention of Kajikawa Noboru, he was finally awarded a 5d diploma, then was promoted to 6d after a match with Takahashi Kinesaburo. The purity of his go made him a popular opponent for younger players trying to get diplomas - victory against him counted high. Another reason was that he never split hairs about fees - he made a small living as a landlord and was modest in his needs. He was a proud person but felt great shame that he did not serve in the Russo-Japanese War. In his late years there was some support for making him Inoue XV but he was overlooked because of his age. He was then also afflicted with an eye disease. Posthumous 7d.

career: He was adopted when very young by a family whose business failed when he was 15, forcing him to leave school and turn to go. At age 18 was sent to be a pupil at the Hoensha through the introduction of Seki Genkichi. There he lost to the women Kita Fumiko and Hayashi Sano and in shame studied so hard he made himself ill. Nakagawa Kamesaburo (head of the Hoensha) wanted to send him home to convalesce but Seki refused as he did not even have a 1d diploma yet. Iwasaki Kenzo agreed with Seki, while admitting that go was obviously not Tanaka's calling. So Tanaka stayed in Tokyo to recover. He transferred to the Honinbo family but was still notorious for excessive study through the night (with Takahashi Kinesaburo, whom he credited for his improvement) - he was often seen sleeping standing up against a pillar in the daytime. He could not sleep properly by day as his bed was in the communal dining room. 1d 1892 or 1893, 2d 1894, 3d 1895, 4d 1898, 5d 1905. He transferred to be a teacher at his own highly popular club in Nagaoka in 1899. His popularity was such that even after his death part of the proceeds of the club was given to his family.

career: Ultranationalist political leader whose party promoted Japanese expansionism on the continent, especially in Manchuria. He supported political exiles such as Kim Ok-kyun (a friend of Honinbo Shuei) and Sun Yat-sen and advised the Chinese government in the 1911 revolution. He remained an eminence grise of Japanese Asian policy even during the war, through his influence over groups such as the anti-Russian Amur River Society. He played go with Inukai Tsuyoshi and Kim (who were evenly matched) though was some way below their level. But he took on a majestic air as a spectator and was dubbed a 見物初段 (Sightseeing 1d) by Shuei.

career: Her original surname was Murata 村田, a sanurai family in Shimosa Province (now Ibaraki Prefecture), but she was adopted at age 6 by Tsuzuki Senshi 5d. As he had retired and she learnt go only at age 14, she did not learn much from him. She played Honinbo Shuei on 7 stones in 1887, as a result of which she became his pupil. She was also taught by the Yasui pupil, Umezu Choko. 1d 1890. She joined Hoensha in 1899. 2d 1901, 3d 1908 and 4d in early Taisho according to one source and 1922 according to another. Her results in the Hoensha were 21-23 and she won the famous women's tournament called Onna Gokaku Oteai in 1907. She joined Doshikai with Kita Fumiko in 1909 and was a regular player there. She briefly took part in Nihon Ki-in games at the time of its foundation (1924), but she spent her last years teaching amateurs and had only one semi-professional pupil (Yoshida Shizu). She remained a spinster and was noted for her great generosity. Posthumous 5d.

died: 1984-05-04 (one source says he lived to 96 but agrees with the year of death)
status: One of the "grand old men" of Chinese go in the 20th century, though a late developer, representing Shanghai (where he died) and playing in tournaments even in the 1960s.
career: He was ranked slightly below Liu Dihuai, with whom he collaborated on several books. His father loved go. He had lots of private students in Beijing and Wang played them as a child but soon surpassed all of them. He went to the Haifeng Teahouse where all the top players in Beijing gathered, to study with his father's approval. He studied with Ying Xingyuan, Yi Yaoqing and Wang Yunfeng, and when Takabe Dohei 5d visited, he played him on three stones. In the civil war period he worked for an agricultural bank in Beijing, but he also took some go pupils. He was runner-up in the 1958 and 1962 National Championships, and played Segoe Kensaku 9d when the Japanese sent a team to Shanghai in 1960-06, winning by one point. Latterly he acted as an editor of the _[_Weiqi_]_ monthly magazine. He died in an accident, not of old age.
name: Wang Youchen
gostyle: Style marked by clarity and order because he was familiar with the old go manuals. Composed. Daring and resolute. Full of drastic measures. Overwhelming attack.

status: Taiwanese-born professional at the Nihon Ki-in Main (Tokyo) Branch.
teacher: Ko Mosei. In Japan, where she was an insei from 2002, she has also studied with fellow Taiwanese O Meien and Rin Kaiho.
career: She learnt go from her father at age 5. At 10 she was 2nd in the world youth tournament. She became potentially the youngest ever female pro when she was top woman in the Japanese pro entrance exam in 2003-08 at age 13 (the previous record had stood for 62 years), and this was confirmed when she formally became　1d in 2004-01 (counted as age 14 years 1 month, though actual start date for playing was 2004-04-01). Her exploit was aided by the fact that the Nihon Ki-in had removed the age limit of 15 for female pros in 2003. 2d 2005, 3d 2006, 4d 2008, 5d 2010, 6d 2012, 7d 2021. She has earned both the Honorary Women's Honinbo and Honorary Women's Meijin titles. As of June 2016 she had held 24 titles, a record for women in Japan. In 2006 she became the youngest winner of a female title in Japan (age 17 in the Women's Pro Saikyo). She became the first woman to hold the three major women's titles (Kisei, Honinbo, Meijin) in 2010-01, and then the first to hold four such titles, in 2016 after adding the Aidu Chuo Hospital Cup.
name: Xie Yimin
note: Until overtaken by Fujisawa Rina in 2014 she was the youngest ever winner of a female title in Japan, aged 17 years 1 month.

origin: Qiantang District, Hangzhou City, Zhejiang Province, China
status: One of China's greatest past players.
career: He regarded Huang Longshi as his teacher and played a famous match on three stones (Games of Blood and Tears) with him at a time when he was assumed to be close to Huang's strength - at least good enough to take 2 stones. Huang was successful and, in one account, Xu is supposed to have poisoned Huang out of envy or to have led him into a dissolute life. Others claim Xu showed his respect for Huang by taking a large handicap. After making his reputation locally, he visited Beijing, China, where high officials vied to play with him. His reputation soared when he easily beat a Korean envoy in the capital who claimed to be the strongest player in the world. It was in Beijing that Xu also bested the veteran guoshou (national champion or meijin) Zhou Donghou. Xu's own ranking as a guoshou is put at around Kangxi 24 or 1685. Xu was also a noted calligrapher and painter, and his tome of 62 commented games _[_Jianshan-tang Yipu_]_ (Go Games from Jianshan Hall - 兼山堂Jiān Shāntángxingyou was his studio name).
name: Xu Xingyou
note: Also known as Xu Yuan 徐远.

status: Japanese professional at the Nihon Ki-in Main (Tokyo) Branch.
career: Learnt go together with his father, Muraji (who reached about 1d as an amateur) at age 7, when his father was ill for a long period. He took lessons from Takeda Itsuko and at 13 started frequenting the Nihon Ki-in Young Players Study Group through the help of the son of Toyama Mitsuru, Toyama Hidezo. He then became a pupil of Mukai Kazuo. 1d 1940, becoming semi-pro and allowed to take part in the Oteai. 2d 1942, 3d 1943, 4d 1945, 5d 1949, 6d 1951, 7d 1954, 8d 1957, 9d 1963. He left the Nihon Ki-in 1947~49 to join Igo Shinsha. One of the post-war Three Crows, along with Fujisawa Hideyuki and Suzuki Keizo. At this point he was nicknamed Yamabe the Uninhibited (Honpou Yamabe) by Gengenshi. He is regarded as one of the best players not to have won a title. For a time he was notorious for living in a hovel in Omori with no telephone, and had to rely on neighbours to relay messages from the Nihon Ki-in or newspapers about game schedules.
name: Yamabe Toshiro
note: He had the nickname Yamabe the Uninhibited 奔放山部 (ほんぽうやまべ).

career: As the eldest son of Yasui IX, he succeeded as family head in 1858 on his father's sudden death. But the succession was not straightforward as he was so young and there were other candidates such as Onizuka Genji and Ebisawa Kenzo, but Sakaguchi Sentoku II and Honinbo Shuwa intervened on his behalf. 1d 1860, 2d 1861, 3d 1862. He played Castle Games from 1860, including the last, as 2d against Ito Showa on three stones. The loss of his mother in 1862 and the fall of the Shogunate created hardship for the family but he continued to play go and by 1872 was 5d. After the death of Ito Showa in 1878 he became the last player alive to have played Castle Games and was venerated accordingly. He joined the Hoensha in 1890 and gave great support. He was promoted there to 6d in 1897 and 7d in 1899. He died suddenly during a game with a pupil with no appointed heir and an adopted son who was poor at go, and so the Yasui family tradition died out.

origin: Tozaka-mura, Hikami-gun (now Aogaki-cho), Hyogo Prefecture, Japan
career: Until the emergence of the modern Chinese he was regarded as the strongest amateur in the world, but he did in fact hold a professional 6d diploma as a guest member of the Kansai Ki-in (and was already given a 3d diploma by the Nihon Ki-in in 1924-11), and was notorious for being able to beat young professionals on handicaps. He was also formally awarded a 7d diploma in November 1976 by the Nihon Ki-in. It was not specified whether this was meant to denote pro or amateur - perhaps deliberately, as in one of the speeches Go Seigen said "we don't know whether he is pro or amateur". He also taught some pros. He was treated as a student of Honinbo Shusai and left Tohoku Imperial University early for this purpose. His fellow students were the likes of Iwamoto Kaoru and Hayashi Yutaro, but he was always below their strength. In 1932 he joined the Nihon Ki-in as editor in chief, in 1934 wrote the first go best-seller, Shin Fuseki-ho, that brought the new opening ideas of Kitani Minoru and Go Seigen to the world, and in 1938 founded and edited (till the war) the journal Igo Shunju in West Japan (where he lived). After the war he founded the journal Kien but resigned after issue #3 and resumed Igo Shunju. He taught the future professionals Kageyama Toshiro and Komatsu Hideki, and also the top amateur Kikuchi Yasuro. He played several games with professionals. His best result was to win on two stones against Honinbo Shusai in 1933, but he also beat Ohira Shuzo with White in 1952. Director of Amachua Igo Renmei (Amateur Go Federation), he was one of the main instigators of the Japan-China go exchanges. Posthumous 8d.

teacher: Cheon Yeong-seon, then (from 1984) Cho Hun-hyeon as a live-in disciple.
career: Learnt go from his grandfather at age 6. Insei 1984, 1d 1986 (aged 10), 2d 1987, 3d 1988, 4d 1989, 5d 1991, 6d 1992, 7d 1994, +9d (by recommendation) 1996. He won the national youth championship and took third place in the World Youth Championships at age 9. He has achieved the fastest Korean promotion to 9d and was then the youngest ever 9d (overtaken by Pak Yeong-hun). He declared his ambition when 1d was to be world number one by age 20 - he achieved his first world championship title aged 16 (3rd Tong Yang Cup, 1992-01) and recorded his 100th title victory in 2001, including a record number of more than a dozen international titles. He was helped by a change in the law that exempted him from full military conscription (due at age 19) because of his "sporting" achievements. He overtook the record of Kim In's 40 consecutive victories in domestic tournaments, recording 41 in 1990. He set a world record in 2002 for the fastest player to reach 1,000 wins - 16 years (he was the third Korean to do this). In 2010-01 he became the second Korean to reach 1500 career wins (vs. 463 losses - Cho Hun-hyeon led with 1812-748-9).

He scored 32 consecutives wins from 25 January to 16 May 2000 (3rd longest run after Yi Ch'ang-ho and Kim In). He set a record as the lowest graded player to win a world championship when he won the Fujitsu Cup in 2002 as 3d, though he was undergraded as he had not been playing in the promotion tournament. In 2009 he took an 18-month break from Korean go in protest at pressure on him to give up a percentage of his fees from Chinese games to the Korean Go Association, to surrender to them control of his game records, and to play in the Baduk League. He continued to play in the China Weiqi League, however. In 2009-12, after reflection, he reapplied for reinstatement and in 2010-01 it was granted conditionally - the conditions being that he gave a percentage of his Chinese earnings, allowed use of his game records and followed the rules for professionals. In 2016, he was defeated in a match against the computer program AlphaGo and shortly afterwards intimated again some dissatisfaction with the organisation of professional go in Korea. In 2019-11 he again announced his decision to retire.

status: Chinese player prominent in the early 20th century.
career: His family traded in silk and salt, and had properties in Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Shanghai, and Hong Kong in China, and in Europe and the USA. They were one of the four richest in Huzhou. Zhang was a go fanatic, and fairly strong but a very fast player. He played Takabe Dohei initially on 3 stones and later on 2 stones. He was later given 3d by the Nihon Ki-in. Because of his wealth he was able to invite strong Japanese players to China, offering not just travelling and subsistence expenses but also prize money. He also supported Chinese players in Shanghai with monthly stipends. He collected Japanese games and so was instrumental in introducing Japanese ideas into China. These books and rare Chinese books he collected were later left to the Shanghai Go Society. In the 1940s he fell ill, losing the use of his lower limbs, and so moved away from Shanghai. He was given a 4d diploma from the Nihon Ki-in by Segoe Kensaku in 1942.
name: Zhang Danru
note: Styled Zhang Jian 张鉴. Brother of Guomintang veteran Zhang Jingjiang (aka Zhang Renjie who was an anarchist and so was a political exile in Japan.

status: Chinese player of the late 17th century.
career: He was a close contemporary of Huang Longshi in the Qing Shunzhi to Kangxi periods 1644~1723) and was regarded as his greatest rival - he was known as the tiger to Huang's dragon. Their games together are greatly prized. He played the "Thirty Games in Paradise Garden" with Huang, of which 25 are extant (Huang played first in 10 and won 8, while Zhou played first in 15 and Huang won 10, the rest being very close). Before Huang, he had famous encounters with Zhou Lanyu. In all, 84 of his games remain, including many with the top players Sheng Dayou, Zhou Lanyu and Wang Hannian. Wu Ruizheng said that whenever he lost, he never despaired and came back again "like a new wave before the previous one had subsided," always bringing forth new ideas. He wrote the _[_Yi Wu_]_ (Go Awakenings) with his games against Guo Bailing, published in the Kangxi era, and works on two-stone and four-stone openings. He appears to have been regarded as the best player in Beijing after Huang's early death, until Xu Xingyou, then in middle age, beat him - Zhou was then known as veteran. He was apparently older than Huang. His life therefore seems to have covered the last seven decades of the 17th century.
name: Zhou Donghou
note: His personal name was Zhou Xun 周勋. Zhou Xihou is often presumed to be his brother but the latest view is that this is apparently a mistake.
